energy to not addrress the real agenda to which they are committed. We must remember that only a very small minority are committed to those groups and their various agendas, hidden and otherwise, and their influence is waning. It is the general population whose misconceptions and superstitious fears must be addressed. <br>
<br>
To do this, the luddite agenda(s) must be exposed, but not belabored. If only luddites, commies, vegans, and nature cultists opposed space nuclear power, we would already have a hotel on Pluto. There is still a good reason not to forget the anti-nuclear movement entirely: It is critically important not to let their anti-corporate, grassroots image go unchallenged. That they receive corporate money is a minor hypocrisy that they can rationalize away by distinguishing between &quot;greedy&quot; corporations and &quot;thoughtful, benign&quot; ones. Their corporate connection extends far beyond funding and career paths. I submit that it is the very heart of the movement, the radical anti-nuclear movement is not the real source of public hostility toward, and fear of, nuclear energy. The radical activists are squatters on the fringes of the Hollywood/Madison Avenue Cultural Axis, eking out contributions and career advancement from the influence of the &quot;corporate media&quot; they profess to hate so much. The &quot;corporate media&quot; have long understood the profitability of fear-mongering, and that is the real enemy. <br>
<br>
We cannot change public perceptions unless we expose and refute the rationale and the propaganda that incite fear of nuclear energy, and the commercial, corporate, motives behind much of that propaganda.  We should attempt to make people think about the real sources of their anti-nuclear perceptions. <br>
&quot;Did thousands really die at 3 Mile Island? Where did I get that idea?&quot; <br>
&quot;Are Hollywood celebrities the real source of my beliefs?Am I just going along with this because it is the<br>
'thing to do'?&quot; <br>
&quot;What did the news really say? Was there something misleading in their presentation?&quot; <br>
&quot;Why would they mislead us about this?&quot; <br>
&quot;Is there a profit in fear-mongering?&quot; <br>
&quot;Will any amount of radiation give my children cancer?&quot; <br>
&quot;How does it compare to hazards that I accept.&quot;<br>
And a pair of questions we might ask, &quot;How many TV commercials do nuclear-energy companies buy?&quot; &quot;How many commercials do anti-nuclear scare stories sell?&quot;<br>
<br>
We should make an effort to acquaint people with the commercial rationale for fear-mongering in general, and anti-nuclear fear-mongering in particular.  This is a difficult angle to prove to those who are unfamliar with it. For many people, it challenges their fundamental view of the world, a view they have never once been asked to question. This worldview includes a massive variety of other media scare stories, from shark-bites to terrorism; as well as urban legends, conspiracy theories, common prejudice and religiously motivated scare stories. <br>
<br>
There are 2 books that I think every pro-nuclear activist should read:<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.basicbooks.com/site/frontlist/014895/014895.html"> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Culture of<br>
Fear</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Barry Glassner</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.salonmag.com/books/feature/1997/12/cov_22feature.html"> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The<br>
Conquest of Cool</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Thomas Frank</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. <br>
<br>
Glassner's book is written from a liberal perspective, but it outlines principles and gives examples that serve to illuminate the real extent of the commercial medias' hold on public perception, and their ruthless profit-driven distortion of those perceptions. Frank's book is<br>
an analysis of cultural history in the 1960s, focusing on the fundamentally commercial nature of the 60s counterculture and, by extension, its offshoots. Neither book addresses nuclear power issues to any great extent, but they are both landmark works in understanding how the human future and the promise of the space age were hijacked by greedy manipulators. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 111<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/19/02 10:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=47.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Real Enemy and some recommended reading</span><hr size=1> That was really an excellently written piece atomic. Keep it up. You have a natural talent for writing and this is an area of human endeavour desperately in need of talented writers. People prepared to go against the ingrained fallacies of the ecowacky propaganda machine.<br>
The media is indeed the enemy. Tragedy and sex sells. For this reason stories of a negative nature concerning nuclear power systems get all the hype. Stories disproving the absurd claims of environmental groups are not seen as newsworthy. Where's the death and mutilation that the masses crave. No reporter wants to waste time on a piece which might end up in the back pages at best. Assuming their editor deems it a public interest story of sufficient value to publish at all.<br>
<br>
My approach has always been to stab straight at the heart of the matter. Talk up the infinite benefits of nuclear spaceflight over conventional chemical boosters and await the cries of 'not nuclear power'. That way it is the other party which has brought up the matter and I can immediately challenge their claim. Unfortunately, not being anything more than a layman in such matters I have trouble being persuasive against a crowd of emotionally enraged anti-nuclear propagandists convinced in their own minds I am the embodiment of Satan.<br>
<br>
To tell the World what we know requires a platform and thanks to Zaphod4468 we now have a better one than that at Yahoo. I'm quite enjoying myself. Currently I am collecting everything related to this topic I can find and posting it. It doesn't matter that there are few members as yet. We have to start somewhere. I plan to keep adding topics until this is the premier nuclear space site on the web. People will see articles here and return to quote them at other boards. If we make this place the most informative site possible then visitors will become interested in what we are doing and gradually it will grow.<br>
